## Model 1
fit1 <- bf(
  yi | se(sqrt(vi)) ~ 0 +
    Lipid_class +               
    Lipid_class:Tissue +         
    Lipid_class:Growth_stage +   
    platform +                   
    (1 | Study) +                  
    (0 + Lipid_class || plant_species) +   
    (1 || plant_species:Tissue:Lipid_class)
)

## Model 2
fit2 <- bf(
  yi | se(sqrt(vi)) ~ 0 +
    Lipid_class +
    Lipid_class:Tissue +
    Lipid_class:Growth_stage +
    platform +
    (1 | Study) +
    Lipid_class:plant_species +
    Lipid_class:Tissue:plant_species
)

## Results
LOO Model comparison - Model 1 is better
Model 1 (Random Effects): ELPD = -8625.4 (SE = 133.9)
Model 2 (Fixed Effects): ELPD = -8635.2 (SE = 134.2)
Difference: 9.8 ± 5.7 (1.7 standard errors)

Bayes R-square - models performed similarly
Model 1: R² = 0.0040 (0.40%)
Model 2: R² = 0.0036 (0.36%)

Pareto k-diagnostics
Both models <1% problematic observations.
Model 1- 99.2%
Model 2 - 99.0%

Variance for model 1 shows appropriate structure with substantial between-study heterogeneity

So, model 1 was chosen.

